From: <VeeWee111(-at-)aol.com>
 re: battery explosion and clutch cable breaks


> Hi John,
> Our clutch cables tend to last well over 30,000 miles.  You might want to
> first hand inspect the tubing for holes worn threw.  If no holes then
install a
> new cable and keep track of how long it lasts before replacing the entire
> clutch cable tubing.  If same happens twice then might try to fix it, and
if thrice
> definitely time to do something.  After all it might have been a fluke
that
> this one cable failed so soon and in the spot it did.  The problem with
> replacing sections of the tubing is that where it is welded back together
will
> possibly be a rough area for the cable to wear on and even when installing
a
> complete tube the welding can melt into the tube and cause the same
problem.
